# Auditoría de Ecosistema: Rand Fishkin
**Plataforma:** LinkedIn
**Filtro Etnográfico:** Cuestionamiento crítico de la "caja negra" de los LLMs (AEO), la defensa de los datos empíricos (cero asunciones) en la creación de Personas y el impacto psicológico del "Juego Algorítmico" en los operadores B2B.

---

### La Falacia de la Citación en LLMs (AI Search)
* **Señal Técnica:** Cuestionamiento fundamental de la correlación entre las "fuentes citadas" por una IA y la ponderación real del modelo para recomendar productos/marcas (Desmitificando el AEO).
* **Contenido Crudo:**
> AI Experts (real ones, plz 😅), I'd love some help understanding how these tools choose answers and whether the citations they give are actually indicative of how they've decided which words to output.
> 
> My Qs specifically:
> 1) if I ask an AI tool what the best noise canceling headphones are and it gives me a list of products, and I then ask for citations, do those links/citations have anything to do with how the model chose those products?
> 2) what about when I ask for a list of brand or product recommendations and the AI tool includes citations in the initial response? Are those necessarily connected to how the brands were chosen? Or are they separate? 
> 3) Tons of SEO and AI marketing folks here on LinkedIn are constantly showing lists of places where citations come from... Is it true that changing how your brand is talked about in those citation-heavy places will have an impact on what the AI tools output? Is it possible/probable that the true sources for the models are disconnected from the cited URLs/domains?

